org.jplot2d.element

Interface Title

  • All Superinterfaces:
    Element, MovableComponent, PComponent, TextComponent
    All Known Subinterfaces:
    TitleEx
    All Known Implementing Classes:
    TitleImpl

    public interface Title
extends TextComponent, MovableComponent
    A text title of plot. A plot may has multiple title. They are always in top-down order.

      • getPosition

        TitlePosition getPosition()
        Gets the current position of this title in a layer.
        Returns:
        the position.

      • setPosition

        void setPosition(TitlePosition position)
        Sets the position of this title. The values can be FREE, TOPLEFT, TOPCENTER, TOPRIGHT, BOTTOMLEFT, BOTTOMCENTER, BOTTOMRIGHT. Only when position is FREE, the title can be located by setLocation(Point2D), setHAlign(HAlign), setVAlign(VAlign) .
        Parameters:
        position - the position of this title.

      • setHAlign

        void setHAlign(HAlign halign)
        Set the horizontal alignment. The alignment can be LEFT, CENTER, or RIGHT. eg, LEFT means the base point is on the left of this title.

        Notice: This method should be called when the position is null, otherwise the behavior is not defined.

        Specified by:
        setHAlign in interface TextComponent
        Parameters:
        halign - horizontal alignment.

      • setVAlign

        void setVAlign(VAlign valign)
        Set the vertical alignment. The alignment can be TOP, MIDDLE, or BOTTOM. eg, TOP means the base point is on the top of this title.

        Notice: This method should be called when the position is null, otherwise the behavior is not defined.

        Specified by:
        setVAlign in interface TextComponent
        Parameters:
        valign - The vertical alignment.

      • getGapFactor

        double getGapFactor()
        Returns the ratio of gap to its height. The default value is 1/4.
        Returns:
        the gap factor

      • setGapFactor

        void setGapFactor(double factor)
        Sets the ratio of gap to its height. The gap is under the title when its position is TOPLEFT, TOPCENTER, TOPRIGHT. The gap is above the title when its position is BOTTOMLEFT, BOTTOMCENTER, BOTTOMRIGHT.
